{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17616426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17616426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:03:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16390"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16390"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.59,0.05,0.14,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16390"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5923"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"},{"type":"tags","id":"7557"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21580"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21582"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after her first seizure. Her medical history is unremarkable and she takes no regular medicines. On examination, her vital signs are stable. Visual field testing demonstrates a right-sided superior quadrantanopia. Magnetic resonance imaging shows a lesion in the left temporal lobe affecting the optic radiation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the expected visual field defect?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contralateral inferior quadrantanopia","Contralateral superior quadrantanopia","Bitemporal hemianopia","Contralateral homonymous hemianopia","Ipsilateral superior quadrantanopia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe optic radiation contains nerve fibres that carry visual information from the lateral geniculate nucleus to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe. These fibres follow a distinctive path, with some forming an anterior loop (Meyer\u0027s loop) through the temporal lobe before turning posteriorly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral superior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E results from lesions affecting Meyer\u0027s loop in the temporal lobe. This occurs because the fibres that loop through the temporal lobe carry information from the superior retinal quadrant (which corresponds to the inferior visual field).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral inferior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with parietal lobe lesions affecting the optic radiation, as these fibres carry information from the inferior retinal quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E typically results from lesions affecting the optic chiasm, such as pituitary tumours compressing the crossing fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral homonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with complete unilateral interruption of the optic tract, optic radiation, or occipital cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral superior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E is anatomically impossible as all post-chiasmal lesions cause contralateral visual field defects due to the crossing of fibres at the optic chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A lesion in Meyer\u0027s loop of the optic radiation causes a contralateral superior quadrantanopia due to its unique course through the temporal lobe.","The optic radiation curves anteriorly in the temporal lobe before turning posteriorly to reach the occipital cortex.","Post-chiasmal lesions always cause contralateral visual field defects due to crossing of fibres at the optic chiasm."],"references":["Freddi TAL, Ottaiano AC. The Optic Nerve: Anatomy and Pathology. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2022 Oct;43(5):378-388. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2022.04.006. Epub 2022 Apr 13. PMID: 36116850","Takahashi M, Goseki T, Ishikawa H, Hiroyasu G, Hirasawa K, Shoji N. Compressive Lesions of the Optic Chiasm: Subjective Symptoms and Visual Field Diagnostic Criteria. Neuroophthalmology. 2018 Sep 11;42(6):343-348. doi: 10.1080/01658107.2018.1438477. PMID: 30524487; PMCID: PMC6276958","Wall M. Perimetry and visual field defects. Handb Clin Neurol. 2021;178:51-77. doi: 10.1016/B978-0-12-821377-3.00003-9. PMID: 33832687","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16390"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T21:55:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-27T21:56:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9081"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","nam